segments.text: And I think it was a grave mistake for these fraternities to exist on this campus.
In your student days there was a bonfire.
Yes.
Describe if you were... We used to go out and gather all kinds of trash.
And we go to these, they had a lot of sawmills around here.
And they'd always keep the trash for us.
They knew we were gonna come after it.
So we'd get the trucks and we'd pick up all that stuff and we laid it out.
We didn't build it up.
And they were delighted to have you all haul it away.
Oh, yes.
And we built it up just about the size of the height of a person.
And we started off way up here, as high as we can.
And we'd diminish it down below.
And then we'd start the fire from going down below and let it go all the way up.
I had a great time.
About how long did you all work on it?
A week or a month?
Oh, maybe a couple of weeks.
But when I saw that 110 bonfire that I came here and I saw that with that outhouse on top, you know, I didn't laugh.
I did not laugh.
I said, this is dangerous.
Did y'all put an outhouse on bonfire when you were here?
No, we didn't.
We didn't do anything like that.
And did almost everybody work on bonfire then?
Well, I would say it was a freshman deal more than anything else, but everybody really did work on it.
And it was on the drill field?
It was on the drill field.
Then did y'all have yell practices?
Oh, yes, we had yell practice.
We didn't have midnight yell practice.
We had yell practice, but it was all done before the game or something like that.
And if it were a night game, I would have it before the game.
And was Yale practice held on the steps of the Y?
Steps of the Y, that's right.
Did y'all throw Yale leaders in the fish pond?
No, I don't think we did anything like that.
Were they called Yale leaders?
Yes.
And did y'all have hand signals?
Oh yes, same thing we got now.
What was your favorite Yale?
Did you have a favorite?
Oh no, all of them were good.
You know the spirit of Aggieland came in way after I graduated.
We had the hullabaloo, connect, connect, we had the band playing songs and so forth.
We didn't have too many.
Did you all talk about the twelfth man?
12th man came in in 1921, wasn't it?
The 12th man was betrayed, but not like he's betrayed now.
How was he betrayed then?
Just as a reference.
The games were played at Kyle Field.
Did just about everybody in the community go to the games?
I think so.
I worked 25 cents an hour when I was a freshman laying the seats to the new Kyle Field.
I laid a lot of seats.
Now, originally the stadium was part of Dean Kyle's agricultural area.
Yeah.
Were there any ag fields down in that part of the campus still when you got here?
No.
It was just Kyle Field.
Where was the baseball stadium then?
Or baseball diamond I should say.
Baseball diamond was adjacent to Kyle Field as I recall.
They just had a little stand up that wouldn't hold 100 people.
And basketball was
Basketball was in the, in that, what's the name of it?
I want to say Downs Notatory, but that's not the right name.
Basketball was.
Did you and your buddies go to basketball games?
Oh, yes.
Did y'all make a lot of noise?
Oh, we always made noise.
Who were the favorite opponents then in athletics?
Well, I was on the freshman baseball team, and I tell this story, which is funny in a way.
And we had a coach by the name of Bender, I think it was.
He was an Indian.
Chief Bender, we'd call him.
So I was an outfielder, and I was fairly good.
So I told them, I said, Coach, I'm not going to come back and play next year.
Why?
Well, my studies are getting pretty hard.
I don't have the time.
So I said, OK, all right.
So we were playing TCU, the last game.
We had a man on second and a man on first.
And I said, he was looking for a pinch hitter.
I said, Coach, let me hit.
I'll bring him in.
Let me hit.
And finally, he said, OK.
So to make a long story short, I struck out.
Now he was going this way to the TCU coach to say goodbye, and I was coming this way back to the dugout.
So we met.
He looked at me and he just used one word.
He said, shit.
So that was the end of your athletic career?
That was the end of my baseball career.
Oh, I did.
I went out for track when I was a freshman.
Was Andy Anderson a... Andy Anderson.
He was a coach, I think.
Track coach.
Track.
Describe him.
Oh, he was a different...
He was a man that wasn't too big by your size, I think.
Nice guy?
Great guy.
Great guy.
See, he's the one that Coach Bible told in Dallas...

to go up in the stands and get to come down and put on his uniform because he had played football over at Mississippi College where they had too many guys get hurt and Mississippi State then beat them.
And that's why Coach Bible wanted him to put on the uniform.
I remember whenever we had a little track meet that hit those of us who were runners.
He'd get us underneath the stand and give us a tablespoon full of honey.
I mean it like that.
He said, he'll do it 10 minutes or 15 minutes before he's supposed to run.
He said, but that honey goes into the system so fast.
He said, it gives you energy.
Do you think it did?
Sure it did.
I still believe it to this day.
Whenever I have honey in my office, whenever I have a downer, I fill that field.
After a day's work, I fill down.
I take a teaspoonful of honey.
And that field house was DeWare Field House, wasn't it?
I think you're right.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Describe the Aggie band in that era, in your student days.
How big was it?
What did it do?
Oh, it wasn't as big as it is now, of course, but it was there.
They did their job.
Did you all respect them?
Oh, sure, we respected the band.
Were they called BQs then?
I don't remember.
See, later, World War II, they're called BQs, band queers.
It's a strange kind of respect.
No, we respected the man.
I don't think I ever heard anybody say derogatory remark on the man.
Among the students, what was the most respected student body leadership position?
Corps Commander?
The Corps commander had a lot of leadership, you might say, emulated leadership.
But I think the president of this class.
Oh, really?
Of the senior class?
Oh, yeah, president of the senior class.
I'm trying to think of his name.
Howe, Howe, H-O-W-E.
Okay.
Anyway, he would meet with us.
The corps commander didn't meet with you.
I see.
Corps commander had to do his special work and that is see to it that the military science and tactics were taught and that discipline was carried out and things like that.
Did you all elect the student?
Oh yes, we elected them.
Was it a show of hands or a ballot?
Now you got me there.
I forgot.
And the corps commander was...
I forgot.
I forgot.
I don't think it was...
I don't know.
I don't know.
I can't answer that.
Were there some...
Were there the sons of some famous Texans here when you were here?
Sons of rich Texans or important politicians?
There were a lot of rich Texans, sons of rich Texans, but it's a funny thing about that.
Once the student has been described or dedicated
in a way that he was classified as wealthy.
He wasn't contacted too much.
Students stayed away from him because they couldn't match his dollars.
It's funny.
The same thing goes on today.
Were there any Jewish students here then?
Oh yes.
Were they accepted?
I know there were.
There were no defamation taking place.
I don't think, you know, the whole time I was here, the five years, I don't think that I heard very much racial or any kind of defamation on groups.
We loved each other, you know.
When you only have 2,000 in the school, you're not going to go around causing a lot of damage.
About how many students had a car?
Not many, and they could not park.
They could not park on the campus.
No way.
Where did they keep their car?
I don't know, but you couldn't park on the campus.
My senior year, I was able to buy one of those Ford, flip one of those Fords.
I remember paying them $75, and I was going to pay them $375, and I had to keep it outside the campus.
You could not keep a car on the campus.
Have you heard that before?
No, I did not know that.
You check it.
So it was a school rule.
School rule that no student could keep a car on the campus.
Well, where did you park your car then?
I parked it outside.
All right.
I found the place someplace and kept it outside maybe without any cover, but you could not.
I remember that distinctly.
Did you ever go to, was it called the Quack Shack then?
I don't remember anything like that.
The health center, what was the campus medical service?
Was there a doctor here?
Dr. Marsh?
There was always a doctor here.
And where was his office?
I think it was the administration building.
Oh, okay.
Okay.
Was the Aggieland Inn built yet over at Northgate, a place for people out of town to spend the night?
No.
No, no.
Where did a visitor stay when they came to?
In Bryan.
In Bryan?
Navasota, Hearn.
We didn't have anything around here.
uh and uh most people arrived at the college railroad station most of them rode the train and a lot of them drove and during the graduation then of course everybody had were was permitted to park
But I remember distinctly, and I'd like for you to check that, that you could not park any car, no student could park any car on the campus.
Did you have any dates while you were a student?
Oh, yes.
Where did you get those dates?
Navasota, Hearn, and Bryan.
How did you make first contact with them?
Of course, during the freshman year, I didn't do much of anything.
I didn't have time.
I just worked, worked.
Sophomore year, I was still working.
But anyway, I met people here and there.
And would somebody say something about going to Hearn, that they had a little party, I'd go over there.
And if I met some young lady that I thought might be interested in me, I made advances that way.
And in my senior year, I went with a nice lady from Bryan.
She was very beautiful.
Where would y'all go on a date?
Well, they had places in Bryan you could go to, a lot of places to eat.
Were there places to go dance?
All the dances that were held were held here.
What were the big dances?
A special occasion, the ring dance was the biggest.
And we had some other...
Boot dance?
Had boot dance, ring dance.
And how were those dates treated at an A&M dance?
Oh, with great respect.
I don't think there's been any incident where a young lady
declared abuse.
I've never heard of any.
Were there, did you all have girls come down from CIA on the train?
From Denton?
Oh man, I should say so.
They'd come down with them big time.
And how did you get a date with one of them in advance?
Well, one of the students would know somebody up there, and then that student would get in touch with the woman he knows up there, and she would bring just a friend of hers down to meet you.
And that's how it was.
Did they exchange pictures sometimes in advance?
I don't remember.
Where did they stay when they were here, those girls from out of town?
Well, I forgot.
Why in the world did they stay?
But I think they had a place for them, designated.
Well, I know in later years they would vacate a dormitory.
The guys would move out and let the girls stay in one of the...
I don't know.
You ask me a question, I don't know.
We're going to have to cut this now.
All righty.
We'll stop right now.
It's on.
He realized that for Texas A&M to grow and be respected throughout the world, that it had to become a university.
He also realized that the only way it could become a university, it had to go coeducational.
And so when he announced it, there was such a loud noise against it that you wouldn't believe.
Practically every Aggie all over the world said, this is crazy.
What are you doing?
This is a men's school.
Leave it alone.
And I would visit with him, and he'd say, you're going to have to help me, Mike.
You're going to have to help me.
He talked to these people.
You know a lot of them.
Talk to them.
We've got to get this through.
He was afraid that if he just voluntarily said, this is the way it's going to be,
It wouldn't work like he wanted it.
So he had a solicitation program going.
And I mean, I wasn't the only one.
There must have been, he must have selected, I don't know how many.
Talk about this thing.
Talk about it.
And I remember talking to Aggies.
and Beaumont and Houston, Port Otta and elsewhere in that area, and I would go visit and let them know that this is very important.
But even then, when it looked like that it would be welcome, there were still loud noises against it.
You'd be surprised.
They didn't want to change it.
They wanted to keep it a men's school, and they wanted to keep it military.
But there was a lot of them at that time were not military.
That's broken off.
I'm the one that wrote the original report recommending those changes to Mr.
Rudder.
Really?
I was the author of that report for the faculty and staff.
For core education?
Yes, sir.
And I now know when we first turned it in, Mr.
Rudder was afraid that he couldn't make it happen.
That was 61.
Yes, sir.
He worked on it 61, 62, and then established it in 63.
That's right.
I now know that one of the key, key influences was Lyndon Baines Johnson.
That apparently, see when Mr. Rutter would go to Washington to try to get money for A&M from the federal government,
He and Lyndon had known each other well, and he had helped Lyndon in that 1948 Senate campaign in the Hill Country.
And apparently, this is circumstantial evidence of what Mr.

Rudder said here and there and there, apparently Lyndon put his arm around him and said, Earl, if you expect to keep coming to Washington to get money out of the federal government from A&M, you've got to get it growing.
It's not growing.
The other schools are passing you by, and you're going to be left out.
You don't have a choice on integration.
The courts have already decided that.
Now, you better admit women because the courts will probably do that.
I'll back you.
John and Nellie Conley are close friends of your wife, Margaret, all four years from the University of Texas.
He'll back you.
Sterling Evans, he and I have done some land deals together.
Your board chairman, he's been for coeducation since he was a freshman there in 1917.
He'll back you.
Buck Wirus.
Yeah.
Wirus will help you.
Olin Teague, your classmate, he'll back you.
Jake Pickle, congressman from Austin, you all have been acquainted since you were eighth graders.
He'll back you.
And another person that sometimes gets left out is the state senator here, Bill Mohr.

yeah the bull of the brazos yeah i remember he was a strong proponent for co-education yeah no i got a lot of flack i was by being the junior member in terms of rank i got to take the minutes and write the report and my last conversation with mr rutter in the spring of 1970 before his death i love to describe it i'm in as chairman of the faculty library committee begging for more money for the library
Mr.
Rudder looked at me and he said, you people always want more money for the library.
Do you think the students have read all the books they've already got?
And I laughed.
And he said, I'll do the best I can.
Then I said, Mr.
Rudder, you remember that report I wrote?
He said, oh, yes.
I said, only you could have made that happen.
He leaned back and grinned and said, why would you say that?
I said, sir, they couldn't say you weren't a Texan, you weren't an Aggie,
you hadn't been in the Corps, you hadn't served your country, that you didn't work hard, that you didn't have a good wife, that you didn't know anybody in Austin or Washington.
And he leaned back and laughed and he said, oh, I never thought of any of that.
No, I think that he was... Well, I'm glad to know that you had something to do with it.
Tell me, I hear or heard rumors
that at a region board meeting, there was some knockdowns between the nine members on that.
Do you know what happened?
I don't, but I understand that Mr. Evans changed two or three votes, that he got some people that were no, he moved them to yes.
And apparently they got some phone calls from maybe John Connolly, that Mr. Evans was a key person in that.

uh a story that was that was trying to i'll tell you right now i i would go around saying god if this thing doesn't work oh we'll never be it we'll never go anywhere in the first draft i put a line that i took out in the final draft i wish i'd left it in i said we are afraid if a m doesn't make these changes it will end up being like the citadel or vmi
As small.
That's right.
Military.
Right.
And as it is, we're a major league player, no question about it.
I love to tell the story.
Do you know Charlie Babcock?
Beaumont?
Yes, sir.
Absolutely.
Okay.
Charlie, he was a good friend.
And you remember, he was one of the opponents.
That's right, he was.
He sent his ring back.
Wyra showed me his ring.
He sent his ring back and his diploma.
He had been the secretary treasurer of the Beaumont A&M Club for 30 years.
That's right.
He resigned that.
He said, I will never, ever again attend anything related to A&M.
Well, he wrote so many letters, I thought he must be a villain with thorns and a forked tail.
I remember that.
I remember that.
All right, the happy ending.
About five years after all of that, I'm to speak at the Beaumont A&M Club on the 50th anniversary of their never having missed a Monday night.
And they were going to honor him as the most
loyal, productive, most hardworking, and he had said, I'm not coming.
I told you, I'm not coming to anything right at A&M.
All right, I go over with Buck Wirus on the A&M plane, and when we get to the Harvest Club in Beaumont, where they were having it, they said, Mr. Babcock's here.
And I said, I want to see that SOB.
I want to see what he looks like.
Well, at the end of the whole evening, as a total surprise, they said, now we'd like
the hardest working Aggie in this room to come up.
Here came Charlie Babcock, wasn't very big.
No, no, he wasn't.
And they said, Charlie, we want to honor you and thank you.
We know how deeply you cared about some of those things, but we hope you understand the changes.
They stood and cheered.
He walked to the microphone and started crying, and I'll never forget what he said.
Please forgive me, ladies and gentlemen.
I was wrong.
All right, as we're coming back on the plane, I said, Wyrus, I don't understand this guy.
I thought he was a villain.
Tell me about him.
He said, well, he went to A&M, he said he thought he majored in business, went to work at the refinery.
He didn't become rich.
He didn't become famous.
But he was a nice guy.
His wife taught school.
Their daughter died one day on the school playground of an unexpected heart problem.
Then their son, while he was at A&M,
dies accidentally at summer camp at Fort Sill,
And then Wyra stopped, and I said, and you're going to tell me he transferred the love he had for his children to his alma mater, and he honestly, sincerely thought A&M was making a mistake.
Wyra said, that's right.
Yeah, he did.
I said, I forgive him.
I forgive him.
I remember Charlie.
Oh, man.
It's funny you called his name.
And the big joke that night, what are the Greek names?
Coconels.
Coconels.
Janelle.
That's right.
Let's call them Pete.
That's right.
Okay, the chairman, the president of the Beaumont A&M Club that night
in talking about co-education, he said, now some of you don't remember that they allowed, when we GIs came back from World War II, our wives could go to summer school.
And tonight at supper, my wife told me she only had 12 hours of credit at A&M, but that she had more grade points than all the Coconos brothers put together.
Well, everybody stood up and cheered.
